File: The Gauteng Liquor Forum is threatening to go to court unless government lifts the current ban on alcohol sales. JOHANNESBURG - Opposition continues to grow over the banning of alcohol sales during the national lockdown. The Gauteng Liquor Forum is threatening to go to court unless government lifts the current ban on alcohol sales. READ: SA Lockdown: No alcohol will be sold The forum represents about 20,000 liquor businesses and argues the ban is unreasonable and unconstitutional. "It is exactly the prohibition on the selling of alcohol by our clients during the lockdown period which is at the epicentre of the present challenge by our clients," the forum said in a statement. READ: SA Lockdown: Criminals target liquor stores It says less restrictive measures could have been taken and argued that they weren't consulted about the decision to extend the lockdown. Meanwhile, Police Minister Bheki Cele says numerous arrests have been made after at least 14 bottle stores were broken into. READ: Decrease in serious crimes due to unavailability of alcohol: Cele He says this is organised crime as some store managers were caught collaborating with two police officers. The officers have since been arrested. Cele says law enforcement will come down harder on shebeens that continue to supply alcohol during the lockdown. He says not only will liquor be confiscated and people arrested, but officers will also destroy the infrastructure. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs. 